Under Regulation “On foreign currency operations associated with the movement of capital” No. 2536 dated 17 December 2013 (the “Regulation 2536”), a loan from Prodigy Finance (as lender) to a resident student (as borrower) is considered to be a foreign currency operation and as such is subject to mandatory filing with the student’s onshore servicing bank and subsequent registration with the Central Bank of the Republic of Uzbekistan (the “CBU”) for the purposes of external debt accounting. The CBU registration is to be carried out by the onshore servicing bank of the student via a straightforward notification procedure. Any further amendments and/or supplements to the loan agreement are subject to the same filing and registration requirements as the original loan. 

Under Civil Code of the Republic of Uzbekistan, effective as of 1 March 1997 (as amended) (the “Civil Code”), the loan agreement must be made in writing (irrespective of the place of its execution and /or governing law) and signed by both parties. Electronic signing (as opposed to conventional signing on paper) is likely to be insufficient for filing purposes. Under Law “On electronic digital signature” No. 562-II dated 11 December 2003 (the “Law”), only digital signatures duly issued by an authorised state registration centre can be used upon signing documentation. In practice, digital signatures are mostly issued to local banks (rarely to commercial companies), and we highly doubt that an individual (although not prohibited by the law) would be able to obtain a digital signature in the registration centre for the purpose of signing the loan agreement with Prodigy Finance. 

In addition, pursuant to Regulation 2536, to file a loan agreement with the servicing bank, (i) a notarised Russian translation (to be prepared by a certified Uzbek translator and notarised in Uzbekistan) or (ii) an original Russian signed loan agreement, must be provided to the Uzbek servicing bank. To get the Russian translation notarised, an apostilled original loan agreement in the English language will be required. This means that Prodigy Finance would need to sign the loan agreement in the presence of a UK notary and get it apostilled. Alternatively, Prodigy Finance can sign the original Russian loan agreement in addition to the English loan agreement. In the latter case, the original Russian translation will be submitted for filing and no apostilisation of the English version would be required.

Once the filing and registration procedures are completed, Prodigy Finance may disburse the funds which shall be first credited to the student’s foreign currency account held with its onshore servicing bank. Pursuant to Regulation 2536, all payments and settlements (including repayment of the loan) under the loan agreement shall be made via the onshore bank of the borrower. No direct transfers from the student's UK account to the designated university and/or direct repayments from the student's UK account to Prodigy Finance are allowed under Uzbek laws. 

Pursuant to Civil Code, the student may authorise its onshore servicing bank to debit its bank account at the request of a third party, provided such authorisation/ instruction is given in writing and/or directly provided for in a bank account agreement executed between the student and its Uzbek servicing bank.   

In view of the above requirements of Uzbek laws (which must be complied with irrespective of the governing law of the loan agreement), we advise that some of the current mechanisms under the proposed loan agreement are not feasible in Uzbekistan. To comply with the above requirements, the loan agreement shall: 

•	provide that the loan funds are first disbursed to an onshore bank account of the borrower held with an Uzbek servicing bank for further transfer to the relevant university; 

•	set as conditions precedent for the disbursement: (i) evidence of filing of the loan agreement with an onshore servicing bank of the borrower; and (ii) a copy of the executed bank account agreement between the borrower and its onshore servicing bank providing for the right of Prodigy Finance (or any other relevant third party) to debit the onshore account of the borrower in accordance with the terms  and conditions of the loan agreement.

•	be made in writing and conventionally signed by both parties;

•	be either translated into the Russian language following the execution and apostilisation of the English version or signed in the Russian language in addition to the English version.   

In general, we note that the loan itself and the transactions contemplated thereunder are rare and not commonly used in Uzbekistan. We have approached two Uzbek banks (which are most prominent for their foreign economic activity) to discuss the feasibility of the purported loan in Uzbekistan. Both banks have confirmed that they have never carried out such operations with individuals in practice and would need to seek advice from CBU due to the lack of experience and certain “grey” areas of the law. We therefore strongly advise that a draft loan agreement be provided to the borrower’s onshore bank for review prior to the execution to avoid any issues with the filing. 

Please note that our advice is based on the assumption that Prodigy Finance, who we understand will be a signatory to the loan agreement, is not incorporated and does not use bank accounts held in the following UK overseas territories and administrative units:

(i)	Anguilla;

(ii)	Bermuda;

(iii)	British Virgin Islands;

(iv)	Montserrat;

(v)	Gibraltar;

(vi)	British Indian Ocean Territory (Chagos Archipelago);

(vii)	South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands;

(viii)	Turks and Caicos Islands;

(ix)	Cayman Islands;

(x)	Channel Islands (Malvinas Gerisi, Jersey, Sark);

(xi)	Isle of Man.

The above territories are considered off-shore territories under Uzbek laws. Transactions with companies incorporated in off-shore zones and territories, as well as transactions with bank accounts held in such zones and territories are subject to very strict control and monitoring in Uzbekistan, as well as practical restrictions set by the local banks. If necessary, we would be happy to elaborate on the issue in more detail upon request. We confirm that South Africa is not an off-shore territory under Uzbek laws. 

Any other terms and conditions of the loan (i.e., interest rate, amount and maturity period, repayment, termination, etc.) may be determined by the parties in an agreement. The terms of the loan agreement may be amended from time to time by signing of a supplemental agreement between Prodigy Finance and the student.

