Note that lending business, including consumer credits, requires a banking licence in Austria. As a general rule, Austrian regulatory rules (in particular banking supervisory laws) apply to business conduct in Austria. The following principles apply to the question whether banking business is conducted in Austria:
(i)	the place where the offer to enter into a transaction agreement is extended or accepted (e.g., the place of execution of a loan agreement) is in Austria;
(ii)	the place of performance (e.g., place where disbursements and repayments under a loan are made) is in Austria;
(iii)	purpose of the transaction (e.g., financing business activities in Austria);
(iv)	assets located in Austria are provided as a security interest (e.g., Austrian real estate); and
(v)	business is actually conducted in Austria (e.g., negotiations take place in Austria).
The above linking criteria have to be assessed on a case by case basis; the more criteria apply, the higher are chances that business in conducted in Austria (“Linking Criteria”). Please note that the conclusion of a binding agreement is no precondition for the application of the Austrian banking supervisory laws. 
Considering the above, we cannot exclude that Austrian regulatory rules apply to Marketing as set out in the instructions. Prodigy would therefore need to set up an Austrian bank. This requires a license granted by the Austrian Financial Market Authority (Finanzmarktaufsichtsbehörde). Setting up an Austrian bank will take six months to a year, often considerably longer. Minimum capital requirements for a banking license is EUR 5 million. We estimate additional costs for external advice, filing fees, etc. to amount to another EUR 500K to EUR 1 million. 
Alternatively, Prodigy may passport a license covering credit business from e.g. the UK (or another member state of the EU) to Austria.

The solicitation and granting of loans to Trinidad and Tobago residents is regulated under the Financial Institutions Act (“FIA”) as it falls within the definitions of both banking business and business of a financial nature.  The FIA, however, does not expressly define what activities constitute solicitation and it is therefore open to interpretation. This is therefore a grey area. Prodigy’s proposed marketing activities includes sending electronic communications to students resident in Trinidad and Tobago who wish to apply for a loan whilst they are in Trinidad and Tobago. In addition, pre-contract formalities may be completed by the student in Trinidad and Tobago. Whilst, the FIA does not expressly regulate electronic/internet communications and in the absence of an express definition of solicitation in the FIA it is arguable that the regulator, the Central Bank of Trinidad and Tobago, may still form the view that Prodigy’s conduct of sending these communications may amount to solicitation of loans from Trinidad and Tobago students whilst they are resident in the jurisdiction. To comply with the requirements under the FIA, Prodigy must be licensed to conduct banking business and/or business of a financial nature. In order to obtain a license, Prodigy must:
a.	incorporate a local company in Trinidad and Tobago or register as a branch/external company; and
b.	submit an application to the Central Bank of Trinidad and Tobago which is accompanied by a statement of the applicant’s name and the address of its—
i.	registered office in Trinidad and Tobago; or 
ii.	principal office outside Trinidad and Tobago;
iii.	the name, address, nationality, experience pertaining to each director and officer or proposed director and officer and all existing and proposed shareholders holding five per cent or more of any class of shares in the case of an application by or on behalf of a company; or
iv.	the principal representative or proposed principal representative under section 18(2) and any other officers who will be resident in Trinidad and Tobago in the case of an application by a foreign financial institution;
v.	a concise history of the applicant’s business experience;
vi.	a certified statement of the applicant’s ability to meet the requirement of a minimum stated capital or assigned capital of not less than fifteen million dollars or such increased amounts as may be required pursuant to section 16(4), 17(7) or 18(4);
vii.	a certified copy of the articles of incorporation or continuance, bye-laws or other constituent document;
viii.	in the case of an application by or on behalf of a company that has been carrying on business prior to the application, a copy of its financial statements and the auditor’s report thereon for the three consecutive years immediately preceding the application, except that where the local company has been functioning for less than three years, a copy of financial statements and the auditor’s report thereon for each year it has been in operation shall be sufficient;
ix.	such further information as the Central Bank may require;
x.	Application fee of TTD10,000.00 and an annual fee of TTD100,00.00

